Machine Learning on the HuMet dataset

Andrea Cabbia

1 November 2016

In this example, we are going to use a dataset generated during the HuMet study: 15 young men, metabolically healthy and with normal BMI (20 – 25 kg/m2), were recruited within a very narrow age range (22–33 years). The volunteers underwent 4 different nutritional challenges, (Fasting, Liquid diet, Lipid test, Glucose test), as well as a Physical exercise test and a Stress test over the time course of 4 days. For each volunteer 56 blood plasma samples were collected during the study. The analyses yielded qualitative and quantitative information on about 160 metabolites.

The aim here is to predict the metabolic status (or Challenge) from a single observation. We will be using multiclass classification algorithms and feature selection algorithms.

The first step is to import all the libraries that we will need:

#for knn imputation of missing values
library(DMwR) 
#for some useful data-wrangling functions
library(dplyr)
#for LDA function 
library(MASS)
#for knn classifier
library(class)
#for feature selection
library(Boruta)
library(rFerns)
library(msgl)
#for nicer tables in the pdf
library(pander)

Import the data and fill missing values using K-NN imputation: This functions replaces missing values with the average of the K closest observations (K=2 in this case)

set.seed(1) #for reproducibility
panderOptions("table.split.table", Inf) #graphical option for tables
data = read.csv('/home/andre/datasets/plasma.csv')
plasma = knnImputation(data,k=2)

Now we have a better idea of the contents of the dataset, but some preprocessing is needed:

#drop Sample.code and Subject var columns
plasma=dplyr::select(plasma,-Sample.code) 
plasma=dplyr::select(plasma,-Subject)

For our machine learning tasks, we need separated sets for training and validation. Here we build an index and split the dataset in trainig and testing set (70% training/30% testing)

idx=sort(sample(nrow(plasma),nrow(plasma)*.7))
train=plasma[idx,]
test=plasma[-idx,]

The following step is to prepare the inputs (data matrix, X) and the outputs (label vector, Y):

train.X=dplyr::select(train, -Challenge)
train.Y=dplyr::select(train, Challenge)
test.X=dplyr::select(test, -Challenge)
test.Y=dplyr::select(test,Challenge)

We are now ready to start!

First, a comparison between 2 multiclass classifier algorithms: K-nearest neighbor and Linear Discriminant Analysis.

K-Nearest Neighbor is a non-parametric algorithm. The algorithm finds the K closest training examples in the feature space. An object is classified by a majority vote of its neighbors, with the object being assigned to the class most common among its k nearest neighbors (k is a positive integer, typically small). If k = 1, then the object is simply assigned to the class of that single nearest neighbor.

Let’s run the classifier: (K=3)

knn.pred=knn(train.X,test.X,t(train.Y),k=3,prob=TRUE)

The results of the classification can be seen in this table (real classes vs predicted classes):

The accuracy is very low: The flexibility of the non parametric approach in this case has brought no benefit.

Let’s try with another different algorithm:

Linear Discriminant Analysis(LDA): this method finds a linear combination of features that gives maximum separation between the centers of the data while at the same time minimizing the variation within each group of data. The resulting combination may be used as a linear classifier, or, more commonly, for dimensionality reduction before later classification.

LDA is similar to Principal Component Analysis, but while PCA tries to retain most of the variance in the data, LDA tries to retain most of the between-class variance in the data.

plasma.lda=lda(Challenge~.,data=train) 
plot(plasma.lda,cex=1.2,abbrev=T,col=as.integer(train$Challenge))
legend(x="topleft",c("Fasting","liquid diet","Glucose test","Lipid test","Physical activity test", "stress test"),col = as.integer(train$Challenge))

# For some reason I can't make the legend to show up... Zoom on the plot to see class labels:

In the plot above we can see how, in the linar discriminant space, the classes are fairly separated: i.e. in LD1 vs LD5 the green and purple clusters (lipid_test and stress_test) are well separated, both between them and from the other clusters.

But, besides visualization and dimensionality reduction, we are intersted in getting a prediction:

plasma.lda$prediction=predict(plasma.lda,test)$class

The second part of this study is about feature selection, another very important task in machine learning: It’s an important aspect of model building, it helps in building predictive models free from correlated variables, biases and unwanted noise.

We will try 2 different algorithms: the first (the Boruta package) uses a random forest classifier and then applies a feature importance measure (the default is Mean Decrease Accuracy)

boruta.train=Boruta(Challenge~.,data=plasma,doTrace=1,getImp=getImpFerns)
final.boruta=TentativeRoughFix(boruta.train)
final.boruta
## Boruta performed 99 iterations in 16.92864 secs.
## Tentatives roughfixed over the last 99 iterations.
##  129 attributes confirmed important: Arg, C0, C10, C10.1, C12 and
## 124 more.
##  35 attributes confirmed unimportant: C5.1, HDLA, HDLD,
## HDLquantity, PC.aa.C28.1 and 30 more.

The function performed a first selection of the features, labeling some of the variables as tentative when the results were not significant enough. The function ‘TentativeRoughFix’ tries to assign these variables to one of the two classes (Connfirmed or rejected) but with lower accuracy. This could explain the high number of features selected as ‘Confirmed’ (129/164)

This is probably due to the fact that Boruta’s algorithm finds all the features relevant to the response variable y, regardless of the fact that they may be (strongly) correlated.

For a more aggressive feature selection we will consider Logistic Regression with sparse group Lasso penalty: Using the lasso penalty allows to shrink the coefficients, setting many of them to zero. the algorithm has 2 important parameters:

Alpha: controls the kind of penalty applied: 1 = lasso (l1 penalty), 0 = group lasso (generalization of lasso, all coefficient in a group (i.e correlated) are shrinked together), intermediate values in the range (0,1) correspond to sparse group lasso (sparsity both with respect to which groups are selected, and which coefficients are nonzero within a group)

Lambda: controls the complexity of the model, or the number of features dropped. If it’s close to zero, many coefficients will be set to zero. To find the best lambda we use 10 fold cross-validation:

lambda=msgl.lambda.seq(train.X,t(train.Y),alpha=0.25,d=50,lambda.min=1e-4)
fit.cv=msgl.cv(train.X,t(train.Y),fold=10,alpha=0.25,lambda=lambda)
## Running msgl 10 fold cross validation (dense design matrix)
## 
##  Samples:  Features:  Classes:  Groups:  Parameters: 
##        588        165         6      165          990

We have now cross validated the models corresponding to the lambda values, one model for each lambda value. Here is a summary of the validation process:
